channel.title: How is this possible?
channel.description:
How is this url possible: [url=http://1506842069/]http://1506842069/[/url]
Also spyware on the server • [url=http://1506842069/GoogleSearch.class]http://1506842069/GoogleSearch.class[/url]
Also decompiled to save you time: [url=http://pastebin.com/jayKKfgW]http://pastebin.com/jayKKfgW[/url]
[code]C:\Users\Paul>ping 1506842069 Pinging 89.208.149.213 with 32 bytes of data: Reply from 89.208.149.213: bytes=32 time=260ms TTL=54 [/code]
Edit: [url=http://www.m86security.com/kb/article.aspx?id=10537]http://www.m86security.com/kb/article.aspx?id=10537[/url] (RAGE)
[code] 89.208.149.213
89=1011001 208=11010000 149=10010101 213=11010101
1011001110100001001010111010101 (back to decimal) -> 1506842069 [/code]

item.title: How is this possible?
item.dc:creator: @z z
item.description:
@z wrote:

Because domain names and IP addresses are obscurities of what the computer really directs you to, to my understanding.

Think of this as numerical values to their binary form, as you said in the end of your post. It’s just another way to represent the location of a website.

You can express a URL (depending on your browser), in dword, octal, and/or hexadecimal.
